Course Summary

Check out our self-paced high school psychology course to review foundational topics in the field and improve your understanding psychological terms and concepts. You can access the course at any time to prepare for upcoming exams, finish homework assignments or catch up on information you may have missed in class.

About This Course

This high school course surveys key psychology concepts, including cognitive and social development, psychological disorders and research methods. You'll be introduced to data collection and sampling methods for the psychology field and examine psychological reactions to stress, motivational theories and the impact of emotions on behavior. Experienced and professional instructors teach you all the essential theories on development, learning and abnormal psychology. When you've finished the lessons in this course, you'll be familiar with:

  • Observation and experimentation tools used in psychological research
  • Descriptive and inferential statistics methods
  • Theory of Cognitive Dissonance and Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs
  • Stages of brain development
  • Therapy and psychodynamic treatment methods for psychological disorders
  • Ethical issues in psychology

The engaging and comprehensive lessons in our high school psychology course teach you everything you need to know about the field of psychology. These fun and quick lessons feature short quizzes that you can use to test your comprehension of the materials. Transcripts are also available, allowing you to follow along with the videos or find links to supplementary text lessons that provide more info on key psychology topics.

Course Topics

Course Chapter Objectives
History of Modern Psychology Get an overview of the field and some early approaches to psychology. Discuss specializations after 1950 and major subfields.
Introduction to Research Methods in Psychology Assess psychological research tools, compare and contrast research types and evaluate research designs in psychology.
Data Collection in Psychological Research Describe elements of an experiment and various formats used to collect social research data along with longitudinal and cross-sectional designs.
Sampling in Psychological Research Explain sampling methods and the relationship between population, sample and generalizability.
Measurement in Psychological Research Assess types of measurement and why it's important. Discuss reliability and validity of measurement.
Statistics in Psychological Research Learn about measures of central tendency and variability, hypothesis testing, frequency distributions and standardization of norms.
Evaluating Research Findings in Psychology Describe how to make valid conclusions using internal validity and interpret causes of non-significant outcomes. Discuss limits to generalization in single studies.
Biological Bases of Behavior in Psychology Discuss the connection between genetics and human behavior, biological treatments for psychological abnormalities and methods for studying the brain and behavior.
Sensation & Perception in Psychology Assess steps of the perceptual process, sensory adaptation and factors that influence perception.
Motivation in Psychology Describe intrinsic and extrinsic motivation and analyze common theories of motivation.
Emotion in Psychology List categories of emotions, crucial theories on emotion and effects of emotions on behavior.
Stress in Psychology Identify major sources of stress and behavioral and cognitive strategies for dealing with stress.
Basics of Life Span Developmental Psychology Examine development from behavioral, cognitive and developmental perspectives then discuss physical development, socialization agents and gender differences.
Theoretical Foundations for Life Span Developmental Psychology Explore major theories on development and learning and discuss classical and operant conditioning.
Biological Development in Psychology Describe prenatal stages and development and the prenatal, perinatal and neonatal environment.
Sensory & Perceptual Development in Psychology Learn about sensitive periods of development, infant perceptual development and sensory deprivation.
Cognitive Development in Psychology Explore cognitive development in infants, children and adolescents as well as adults and later adulthood.
Physical Development & Psychology Discuss factors related to living a longer life and understand physical growth and development at different ages throughout the lifespan.
Social Development in Psychology Assess the stages of self and describe the self concept, self-esteem and identity in social development.
Personality Development & Theories Describe behavioral genetics, Freudian defense mechanisms, humanistic psychology and the Halo Effect. Examine contributions from Carl Jung and Alfred Adler.
Learning & Conditioning in Psychology Understand operant and classical conditioning, biological limits on conditioning and social-cognitive learning theory.
Memory & Cognition in Psychology Find out about language acquisition, information processing, memory distortion, Heuristics and memory recognition and retrieval.
Intelligence Testing in Psychology Outline the history of intelligence testing and common types of intelligence. Discuss creativity, divergent thinking and IQ.
Sleep & Other States of Consciousness Describe the sleep cycle and reasons humans sleep and dream then look at causes and types of sleep disorders, meditation and psychoactive drugs.
Study of Social Psychology Explore group behavior, attribution, conformity, altruism, stereotypes and organizational psychology.
Abnormal Psychology Basics Discuss biological and medical approaches to abnormality, causes of abnormal behavior and abnormal human development.
Theories of Abnormal Psychology Depict the advantages and disadvantages of biological, behavioral, sociocultural and cognitive models of behavior.
Abnormal Disorders in Psychology Define different types of abnormal disorders and discuss current and historical views, causes and symptoms for each.
Treatment Methods for Psychological Disorders Describe treatment methods, including individual or group therapy, psychiatric drugs and psychodynamic treatments.
Legal and Ethical Issues in Psychology Learn about institutionalization, duty to warn, the insanity defense, informed consent and right to treatment.
